# Commit Rules

Follow commit rules strictly.

---

# Core Principles

Commits exist to:

- isolate changes
- improve readability
- simplify review
- simplify rollback
- maintain history quality

Never create giant mixed commits.

Avoid:

```txt
feat: update stuff
```

or:

```txt
fix: several changes
```

Each commit should represent one logical change.

---

# Commit Organization

Separate commits by responsibility.

Examples:

Correct:

```txt
feat(auth): create authentication service

feat(auth): create login form

refactor(auth): extract authentication hook

style(auth): adjust login page spacing
```

Avoid:

```txt
feat: authentication and styles and schema and fixes
```

---

# Commit Group Rules

Create separate commit groups for:

Feature:

```txt
feat(scope):
```

Bug fixes:

```txt
fix(scope):
```

Refactoring:

```txt
refactor(scope):
```

Styles and UI:

```txt
style(scope):
```

Documentation:

```txt
docs(scope):
```

Tests:

```txt
test(scope):
```

Performance:

```txt
perf(scope):
```

Build:

```txt
build(scope):
```

Configuration:

```txt
chore(scope):
```

CI:

```txt
ci(scope):
```

Dependencies:

```txt
deps(scope):
```

---

# Scope Rules

Use scope representing domain or feature.

Examples:

```txt
feat(auth):

feat(users):

feat(profile):

feat(products):

feat(api):
```

Avoid:

```txt
feat(code):

feat(project):

feat(update):
```

Scope must be meaningful.

---

# Commit Message Rules

Structure:

```txt
type(scope): short description
```

Examples:

```txt
feat(profile): create profile edit form

fix(auth): handle expired token

refactor(users): extract user service

style(dashboard): improve card spacing

test(products): add product hook tests
```

Rules:

- lowercase only
- concise
- imperative mood
- max ~72 characters
- no punctuation at end

---

# Multi-Commit Rule

If changes affect multiple domains:

Separate:

Bad:

```txt
feat(auth): create login form and adjust navbar and update tests
```

Good:

```txt
feat(auth): create login form

style(navbar): adjust navbar spacing

test(auth): add login tests
```

---

# Pull Request Rules

PR should group related commits only.

Example:

```txt
PR:

Authentication Feature

Commits:

feat(auth): create auth service

feat(auth): create login form

feat(auth): create auth hooks

test(auth): add auth tests
```

---

# Final Rule

Commit history should explain project evolution without opening files.

A developer should understand:

- what changed
- why changed
- affected area

by reading commits only.